\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
The why, the how, and the when to impute: a practitioners’ guide to survey-to-su
rvey imputation of poverty
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The authors acknowledge financial support from the World Bank.
 We thank Chris Elbers, Roy van der Weide, Sergio Olivieri, Hai-Anh Dang,
 and Nobuo Yoshida for comments.
 We also thank participants of the S2S workshop held at the World Bank.
 Additionally, we thank Luis-Felipe Lopez Calva, Gabriela Inchauste and
 Maria Eugenia Genoni for providing support and space to pursue this work.
 Any error or omission is the authors’ responsibility alone.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Paul Corral, Andres Ham, Peter Lanjouw, Leonardo Lucchetti, and Henry Stemmler
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Paul Corral, Leonardo Lucchetti, and Henry Stemmler are part of the World
 Bank.
 Andres Ham is of Universidad de los Andes, and Peter Lanjouw is part of
 Vrije Universiteit Amsterdam.
 Corresponding author: Paul Andres Corral Rodas, 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
name "pcorralrodas@worldbank.org"
target "pcorralrodas@worldbank.org"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Accurate and timely poverty measurement is central to development policy,
 yet the availability of high-quality household survey data remains limited—part
icularly in countries where poverty is most concentrated.
 Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation has emerged as a practical response to
 this challenge, allowing practitioners to estimate poverty using surveys
 that lack direct welfare measures by borrowing information from other comprehen
sive surveys.
 A technical guide to the method is provided, revisiting its statistical
 underpinnings and testing its limitations through extensive model-based
 simulations.
 Through model-based simulations, the analysis demonstrates how violations
 of parameter stability, omitted variable bias, and shifts in survey design
 can introduce substantial errors—particularly when imputing across time
 or under economic and structural change.
 Results show that standard corrections such as re-weighting or covariate
 standardization may fail to eliminate these biases, especially when imputing
 across time or under structural change.
 The performance of alternative model specifications is also evaluated under
 various methods, including performance under heteroskedastic errors, non-normal
ity.
 The findings offer practical guidance for practitioners on when S2S imputation
 is likely to succeed, when it should be reconsidered, and how to communicate
 its limitations transparently in the context of poverty monitoring and
 policy design.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
\begin_inset VSpace vfill
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement and monitoring of poverty are central to assessing global
 development progress.
 For the World Bank, whose twin goals include ending extreme poverty, the
 ability to track poverty reduction is fundamental to measuring institutional
 effectiveness and guiding policy decisions.
 Yet, a persistent challenge hampers this crucial task: the limited availability
 of recent, high-quality household survey data that includes information
 that allows for comparable measures of expenditure or income across time.
 This challenge is particularly acute in countries where poverty is most
 concentrated 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DangJolliffeCarletto"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In large, poverty-affected countries, such as India and Nigeria, gaps in
 household survey data have hindered global poverty monitoring.
 Together, these two economies account for a substantial share of the world's
 poor, meaning that they heavily influence global poverty trends.
 In India, official consumption survey data was unavailable between 2011
 and 2022.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 75th round of the NSO Survey of Consumption Expenditure was collected
 in 2017-18 but was not released until after 2024: 
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "https://www.mospi.gov.in/unit-level-data-report-nss-75th-round-july-2017-june-2018-schedule-250social-consumption-health"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In Nigeria comparable survey data for poverty monitoring was absent between
 2009 and 2018.
 These data gaps not only affect our understanding of poverty at the country
 level but compromise our ability to produce reliable global poverty estimates
 and assess progress toward poverty reduction goals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditional poverty measurement relies on household surveys that collect
 detailed consumption or income data.
 These surveys represent substantial investments in both financial and human
 resources.
 They require extensive preparation, careful implementation, and place considera
ble burden on responding households, who must either maintain detailed consumpti
on diaries or participate in comprehensive recall interviews.
 The method of data collection itself can introduce significant biases into
 poverty estimates.
 For instance, consumption diaries – while theoretically more accurate –
 can lead to respondent fatigue and underreporting over time.
 Recall modules, on the other hand, may suffer from memory bias, with longer
 recall periods typically resulting in lower reported consumption.
 Research has shown that simply changing the recall period or the number
 of consumption items can lead to substantially different poverty estimates
 within the same population (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "beegle2012methods"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 These methodological challenges add another layer of complexity to the
 already demanding task of poverty measurement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenges of traditional poverty measurement become particularly acute
 during crises when standard survey operations are disrupted or impossible
 to conduct.
 Armed conflicts, natural disasters, health emergencies, and other humanitarian
 crises often prevent face-to-face household interviews precisely when poverty
 monitoring becomes most crucial.
 The COVID-19 pandemic provided a stark illustration of this challenge,
 as household survey efforts were halted globally at a time when understanding
 welfare impacts was most critical.
 Similar data collection constraints arise in conflict zones, where security
 concerns prevent enumerator access to households, or during natural disasters
 that displace populations and disrupt statistical operations.
 During such crises, policymakers and international organizations must resort
 to alternative methods for estimating poverty.
 Survey-to-survey imputation, often combined with rapid phone surveys or
 other alternative data collection methods, has emerged as a key tool for
 maintaining poverty monitoring during these challenging periods.
 However, these approaches come with their own limitations and potential
 biases that must be carefully considered.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For global monitoring see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mahler_2021"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 Global projections of poverty rely on GDP projections during the pandemic.
 The GDP projection for each country is used to shift the welfare distribution
 of a given country by the GDP per capita growth rate observed between year
 corresponding to the household survey collection and the desired year in
 the future.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation has emerged as a methodological response
 to these data limitations.
 The method is often used as a way to produce poverty numbers when traditional
 welfare data collection is unavailable due to costs, complexity, conflict,
 or other reasons.
 The approach builds upon techniques originally developed for small area
 estimation (SAE) in poverty mapping, pioneered by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and further refined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 S2S imputation enables poverty estimation using surveys that lack direct
 welfare measures by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Developing a predictive model of household welfare using a survey with consumpti
on or income data (the "source" survey) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Applying this model to a different survey containing similar household character
istics but lacking direct welfare (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

target
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 survey)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Generating poverty estimates based on the predicted welfare distribution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While S2S and small area estimation share methodological foundations, they
 serve distinct purposes.
 Small area estimation, as developed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and advanced by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, typically applies nationally estimated models to census data to generate
 precise poverty estimates for small geographic areas.
 In contrast, S2S focuses on predicting welfare in a separate survey, regardless
 of geographic disaggregation.
 One might view traditional poverty mapping as a special case of S2S where
 the target dataset are the different areas of the census and the primary
 goal is obtaining geographically disaggregated estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper first examines the limitations and potential pitfalls of survey-to-su
rvey imputation through rigorous analysis of its fundamental assumptions.
 This is a technical paper that relies on simulated data to conduct experiments.
 In these experiments, the focus is not on traditional concerns such as
 variable selection or model specification, but rather on the method's core
 limitations, particularly for measuring poverty across extended time periods
 or different populations.
 The analysis relies on simulated data to isolate and demonstrate specific
 mechanisms that can generate biased estimates.
 This approach allows for clear illustration of three critical findings:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Standard sampling bias-correction techniques, such as re-weighting to match
 population means, may be insufficient when source and target surveys differ
 fundamentally.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The method's tendency to replicate the welfare distribution of the source
 survey can make it unreliable for measuring changes in inequality and poverty.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The model captures the joint distribution between 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in the source data.
 The parameters corresponding to the source data are then applied to the
 target data, where the only difference is the distribution of covariates,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, unless all the change is captured by changes in the covariates the
 method will likely give biased estimates.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Thus, better communication behind the limitations of the methods are crucial.
 These insights are particularly relevant given the increasing reliance
 on survey-to-survey imputation to fill data gaps in poverty monitoring.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Third, omitted variable bias will likely affect poverty predictions, particularl
y when imputing across time periods that include significant economic shocks
 or structural changes.
 This last finding has important implications for applications that use
 "fast-moving" variables to capture welfare changes,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 refer to expenditure related covariates as fast moving.
 These include dichotomous variables indicating if a household reported
 purchasing a product or not.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 as these variables may introduce bias if they are correlated with unobserved
 factors that affect welfare.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Through systematic examination of these limitations using simplified examples,
 the paper provides practitioners with a framework for understanding when
 and why S2S methods may produce misleading results.
 The results here are of relevance since survey-to-survey imputation has
 become more prevalent in recent times to overcome data scarcity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
T One example is the multiple applications in India, where survey data useful
 for global poverty monitoring have not been released since 2011.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Survey-to-Survey Imputation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Survey-to-Survey-Imputation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Collecting household consumption data is costly and complex.
 Consumption modules typically span multiple domains—food, housing, health,
 education, and more—each requiring detailed recall and careful categorization.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "deaton1998consumption"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 observe, these modules are among the most demanding components of household
 surveys, often encompassing hundreds of items and multiple recall periods.
 This not only increases respondent burden but also drives up implementation
 costs.
 Ensuring accuracy adds another layer of complexity: respondents may forget
 or misreport expenditures, and cultural and regional differences often
 require localized adaptations in survey design.
 Moreover, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "beegle2012methods"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrate, even small changes in how surveys are administered can yield
 significant differences in reported poverty and consumption levels.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because of these challenges, few countries collect comparable welfare data
 frequently.
 Long-term, harmonized consumption trends are the exception, not the norm.
 Yet, policymakers, donors, and development practitioners continually need
 up-to-date poverty statistics.
 To fill this gap, survey-to-survey imputation has become an increasingly
 used method for estimating poverty when consumption or income data are
 unavailable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
S2S builds upon the idea proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro,jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where a linear regression model is fit on a survey where expenditure or
 income are available to determine the joint distribution of expenditure
 or income, and a given set of household characteristics – this survey is
 typically referred to as the source or training data.
 The model parameters are then applied to a separate dataset (the target
 data) where the same set of household characteristics can be found with
 the aim of replicating the welfare distribution via imputation.
 With a simulated welfare in hand, poverty estimates and other welfare indicator
s can be derived from the target data.
 The methods can be applied to contemporaneous surveys or to surveys correspondi
ng to a different point in time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method is useful when applied to contemporaneous surveys to obtain statistic
s across the welfare distribution for indicators that are not available
 in the living standards survey.
 For example, the Demographic and Health Surveys (DHS) provide a litany
 of health related indicators that are not available in most living standards
 surveys.
 This is where S2S comes into play.
 A model trained on the living standards survey and applied to the DHS can
 help us inform about the difference in stunting rates between poor and
 non-poor households or determine how it varies across the welfare distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method is often treated as a prediction exercise and unlike much of
 econometrics, the parameters of the linear regression are not intended
 to capture only the direct effect of the characteristics on welfare (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, p356).
 Nevertheless, the original intent of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was to predict on to the same population.
 As will be later shown, when attempting to predict to a different point
 in time, particularly when considerable underlying changes in the economy
 and society have taken place (droughts, earthquakes, floods, conflict,
 etc.), this assumption can lead to potentially biased estimates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When imputing to a different year, the method rests on the assumption that
 model parameters remain stable—that is, the relationship between household
 characteristics and welfare has not changed.
 This assumption becomes tenuous in settings experiencing structural change,
 economic growth, or major shocks.
 In other words, the method assumes that model parameters remain stationary
 over time – meaning that any observed changes in poverty are solely attributabl
e to changes in the model's covariates, rather than shifts in unobservable
 factors or changing returns to these covariates (Dang, Lanjouw and Serajuddin
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 This assumption becomes particularly tenuous in dynamic economic contexts.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiaensen2012small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 note, such assumptions may be especially problematic in rapidly growing
 economies, where structural economic changes can alter the relationship
 between poverty and its predictors.
 It can also be problematic when a strong shock has occurred between the
 periods – for example, a global pandemic or changes in a country's fragility.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Researchers and practitioners have proposed various approaches to address
 the limitations of S2S in predicting poverty over time.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stifel2007tracking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 advocate for including time-varying variables such as rainfall and prices
 to capture temporal changes.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggest incorporating variables that track economic conditions more directly,
 like indicators on whether the household consumed a given good.
 However, as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 emphasize, without updated training data to re-estimate model parameters,
 the risk of missing significant economic changes remains substantial, even
 with these additional covariates.
 A similar point is raised by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mathiassen2009model"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who emphasizes that the validity of imputations rests on a strong assumption
 of parameter stability and explicitly warns against extrapolating too far
 across time or applying the method when significant changes in welfare
 dynamics or survey design are likely.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2025poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 further note that evidence on the utility of granular consumption predictors
 remains inconclusive, and instead advocate for parsimonious models that
 are easier to implement in surveys and in challenging field conditions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effectiveness of S2S imputation across time has been tested in a range
 of contexts, with results showing both its potential and its limitations.
 While some studies report estimates within acceptable margins of error
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "dang2025poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/roiw.12007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), others find significant discrepancies between predicted and observed
 poverty rates (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "newhouse2014survey"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "https://doi.org/10.1111/roiw.12007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 These mixed findings highlight the need for caution when applying S2S imputatio
n across different periods and economic environments.
 A useful example comes from Malawi, where 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "mathiassen2021predicting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 document their efforts to produce comparable poverty estimates between
 2004 and 2014.
 While their method performed well within individual surveys and with careful
 seasonal adjustment, comparability across survey rounds proved fragile.
 Shifts in survey design and implementation such as shorter questionnaires,
 periods of data collection, changing field protocols, and others led to
 unstable predictor relationships and inconsistent poverty trends over time.
 Even in this relatively well-structured case, the authors conclude that
 S2S imputation should only be used when comparability of predictors and
 survey instruments can be assured (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "mathiassen2021predicting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most evidence on bias in cross-time S2S estimates comes from real-world
 applications where time gaps are large or covariate distributions differ
 substantially.
 For example, Dang, Lanjouw and Serajuddin (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) evaluate S2S using Jordan’s Household Expenditure and Income Survey and
 the Employment and Unemployment Survey; 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "stifel2007tracking"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 conduct similar tests for Kenya; and Dang et al.
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "dang2025poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) apply the method across multiple countries—including Ethiopia, Malawi,
 Nigeria, Tanzania, and Vietnam—reporting estimates generally within acceptable
 error margins.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "christiaensen2012small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 undertakes an empirical validation of survey-to-survey imputation methods
 over time.
 The authors perform survey-to-survey imputation in scenarios where there
 is comparable expenditure data which provides a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 estimate of poverty.
 The authors validate their approach with data for Vietnam and for China
 using rural household panel data.
 In Vietnam, the authors obtain a model using the 1992/93 data and predict
 poverty using the 1997/98 data.
 They note that the method works relatively well and depending on the covariates
 used, differences between predicted and observed poverty rates were on
 average 3.4 percentage points during a period where poverty fell by 23.2
 percentage points.
 For the Chinese regions where the method was tested, the authors also find
 that the methods work relatively well.
 However, depending on the model used, differences between predicted and
 observed rates were considerable.
 This highlights the method's conundrum: different models may generate different
 findings, and at least some models may get it right.
 However, ex-ante, it is very difficult to determine which model will yield
 the most accurate estimates or even the right estimates.
 So far, no foolproof methods or diagnostics exist to reliably identify
 the ideal model, raising fundamental concerns about the robustness of imputed
 poverty estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Applications of survey to survey imputation have also made their way to
 global poverty monitoring.
 For example, until recently every poverty number for India after 2011 is
 based on an imputation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As of this writing, every poverty number for India after 2011 is an imputation.
 These numbers are reported in the World Bank's Poverty and Inequality Platform
 and the source of the poverty rates for the country are not always obvious
 to visitors.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To better understand how such estimates are produced, and the assumptions
 underpinning them, the next section outlines the foundations of survey-to-surve
y imputation, tracing its origins in the broader field of missing data methodolo
gies and clarifying its application in the context of poverty measurement.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The basics behind survey-to-survey imputation (S2S)
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:The-basics-behind"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imputation is a method for filling in missing data.
 According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the first instance of a statistical method to replace a missing value
 dates to 1930,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "allan1930method"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 and the first widespread use of the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imputation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 comes from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "madow1983incomplete"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The method was originally proposed to fill in missing observations and
 considered the nature of the missing data (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "dempster1977maximum"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The goal of multiple imputation is not to create a single prediction, but
 rather multiple imputations to reflect the uncertainty around the actual
 value (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 By generating plausible values for missing data, multiple imputation allows
 for valid estimation and the construction of appropriate confidence intervals
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example, in the case of a regression on agricultural yields the variable
 capturing plot sizes may have missing values and these must be imputed
 with the aim of not losing information as well as obtaining a valid estimate
 of the coefficient for the relationship between land and yields.
 Using multiple imputation in this example, as opposed to just the predicted
 land size, is expected to reduce the rate of false positives.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Type I errors, which occur when a null hypothesis is incorrectly rejected.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The case of a variable that is entirely missing in the dataset was not considere
d by the original multiple imputation literature.
 The academic background for predicting an entirely missing variable in
 a given dataset is more aligned to the small area estimation literature
 (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rao2005small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rao2015small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Perhaps the first instance of survey-to-survey imputation, as is applied
 in this paper, comes from the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which is more aligned to small area estimation and noted by the authors.
 The key difference to small area estimation up to that point was that 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 predicted the variable of interest, consumption, at the household level
 and from that they obtained aggregate statistics based on the prediction
 of consumption.
 While earlier examples exist of combining data from different sources to
 predict household-level variables (e.g., Arellano and Meghir 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "arellano1992female"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), the innovation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 lies in applying models estimated from survey data to census data to replicate
 the full consumption distribution.
 This approach allows for the estimation of poverty and other welfare indicators
 as if welfare data were available in the census itself.
 After refinements by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the work became the basis of what later was referred to as poverty mapping
 in the World Bank.
 The key difference between survey-to-survey imputation and small area estimatio
n is that the latter aims to replicate the welfare distribution for each
 specific area or group of interest, rather than only for the entire population.
 One of the first applications of the methods from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to predict national level poverty can be seen in the work of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "simler2004estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who use the methods to track changes in poverty in Mozambique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation for poverty measurement relies on the
 assumption that a population's welfare distribution can be captured by
 a linear model which is estimated on the 
\begin_inset Formula $source$
\end_inset

 data.
 For simplicity, the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $target$
\end_inset

 is used to indicate when parameters are applied to the target data.
 Hence, the assumed data generating process (DGP) for transformed welfare
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Transformed data is often used as the dependent variable to ensure the model's
 assumptions hold.
 For simplicity, throughout this document the assumed transformation is
 the natural logarithm, although many others are possible.
 Meeting the model's statistical assumptions is crucial for reliable estimation.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 demonstrate that violations of these assumptions, particularly the normality
 of residuals, can lead to biased poverty estimates.
 Their analysis shows that appropriate transformation of the dependent variable
 (household welfare) can significantly reduce such bias.
 When the standard logarithmic transformation proves insufficient, alternative
 transformations may be necessary to better approximate normality in the
 model's error term.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln\,y_{i}=x_{i}\beta+e_{i};\:e_{i}\sim N(0,\sigma_{e}^{2})\label{eq:welfare model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of independent variables common to the source survey and the
 target survey, and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a random disturbance term that is assumed to be distributed i.i.d.
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\sigma_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 as well as the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 parameters are estimated using the source survey or the training data since
 this is the only data where the welfare vector of interest (
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\,y_{i}$
\end_inset

) is available.
 These estimated parameters are then applied to the target data to predict
 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln\,y_{i}$
\end_inset

, and from that poverty or other welfare related indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Because normally distributed errors are assumed in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:welfare model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, although this can be relaxed as later illustrated, for any given household
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the target survey, the probability of being poor for household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 is entirely dependent on its expected welfare, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\beta,$
\end_inset

 and the distribution of its idiosyncratic term, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

, which is assumed to follow 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,σ_{e}^{2})$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
Prob\left(poor_{i}\right)=Φ\,\left(\frac{\ln z-x_{i}\beta}{\sqrt{\sigma_{e}^{2}}}\right)\label{eq:cum prob}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln z$
\end_inset

 is the natural log of the poverty line,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that if the transformation of the dependent variable is not the natural
 logarithm, then this is not valid.
 The poverty line must be transformed in a similar manner as the dependent
 variable.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Φ$
\end_inset

 is the standard normal distribution.
 Consequently, what the method calculates is each household's probability
 of being poor.
 The average probability of being poor across households corresponds to
 the national poverty rate.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that because the only thing differing across households in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cum prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are the characteristics, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

, a proxy means test (PMT) approach that relies only on 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\beta$
\end_inset

 will yield the same household ranking as the survey-to-survey approach
 if the same model is used for either.
 Under a PMT, the threshold is chosen at a given percentile of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\beta$
\end_inset

 so that by construction it yields a desired proportion of people eligible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The implementation of welfare predictions to the target data can follow
 different approaches.
 The most common method, grounded in the multiple imputation literature,
 generates several welfare vectors to reflect prediction uncertainty.
 This approach is aligned to what was implemented in poverty mapping through
 the PovMap software (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and is similar to the methodology used in Stata's multiple imputation
 commands (
\family typewriter
mi regress
\family default
).
 Under this approach, each imputed welfare vector is generated through a
 five-step process:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Taken from 
\family typewriter
mi regress
\family default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "StataCorp2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Obtain model parameter estimates for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 via ordinary least squares fit on the training data (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:welfare model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 ), noted below as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The distribution of the error terms is drawn from its posterior Chi-square
 distribution, where 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is the number of observations in the training or source data, and 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 is the number of covariates in the model:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sigma_{e}^{2*}\sim\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\frac{\left(n-K\right)}{\chi_{n-K}^{2}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
With 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 in hand it is possible to update the variance covariance matrix of the
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 parameters: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta^{*}\sim MVN\left(\hat{\beta},\sigma_{e}^{2*}\left(x'x\right)^{-1}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Then errors are drawn from:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
e_{i}^{*}\sim N\left(0,\sigma_{e}^{2*}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each imputed transformed welfare for household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the 
\begin_inset Formula $target$
\end_inset

 data under imputation 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is given by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln y_{im}^{*}=x_{i_{target}}\beta_{m}^{*}+e_{im}^{*}\label{eq:MI}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hence, for each imputed vector, a new 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2*}$
\end_inset

 is drawn and used to draw 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{*}$
\end_inset

 and a household specific residual, 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 The multiple imputation simulation approach is not necessarily aligned
 to reducing the prediction mean squared errors (MSE), but as noted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the purpose is to minimize the likelihood of false positives, since normally
 the imputed vectors are frequently used for regression analysis.
 Alternatively, step 4 may be skipped and the imputed transformed welfare
 can be obtained from 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{im}^{*}\sim N\left(x_{i_{target}}\beta_{m}^{*},\sigma_{e}^{2*}\right).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An alternative approach, derived from the small area estimation literature,
 treats the source survey as the best representation of the true welfare
 distribution.
 Under this approach, parameters estimated from the source survey are applied
 directly to the target data through Monte Carlo simulation.
 For straightforward indicators like poverty rates, practitioners can simply
 apply the asymptotic formula for expected values (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cum prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The steps are straight forward:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Fit Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:welfare model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to the training data using ordinary least squares to obtain estimates of
 the model parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Each transformed welfare for household 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in the Monte Carlo simulation is given by – note how the coefficients remain
 constant across Monte Carlo simulations:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Monte Carlo simulations are not always necessary and for poverty one could
 immediately apply Eq.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:cum prob"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, for more complex parameters Monte Carlo simulations allow for
 indicators that are difficult to handle analytically.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln y_{im}^{*}\sim N\left(x_{i_{target}}\hat{\beta},\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\right)\label{eq:Fixed}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent methodological advances have expanded model fitting options to include
 machine learning (ML) techniques.
 However, since most ML methods do not make explicit assumptions about error
 term distributions, they cannot directly replicate the multiple imputation
 approach described above.
 Nevertheless, bootstrap-based alternatives exist where draws from the empirical
 residuals are used to obtain a welfare vector (
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{*}=\hat{e}_{j},$
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $j\sim\mathrm{Uniform}\{1,2,\ldots,n\}$
\end_inset

).
 These were implemented in both PovMap (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and Stata's 
\family typewriter
sae 
\family default
command by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "nguyen2018sae"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This bootstrapping approach has proven particularly valuable for regularized
 regression techniques, as demonstrated by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lucchetti2024application"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 with lasso regression,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://github.com/pcorralrodas/lassopmm
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and may be extended to other ML methods such as gradient boosting, random
 forests, or Bayesian additive regression trees.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An additional method that can be paired with machine learning techniques
 as well as OLS, is predictive mean matching (PMM).
 The approach compares the predicted values from the target data to those
 from the training data, specifically by minimizing the absolute difference
 between linear predictors 
\begin_inset Formula $|x_{i_{target}}\hat{\beta}-x_{i}\hat{\beta}|$
\end_inset

.
 Once a specified number of nearest neighbors is identified, one of the
 actual observed welfare values is randomly drawn 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 PMM is notably less sensitive to model misspecification and is robust to
 back transformation (ibid).
 For instance, models estimated on 
\begin_inset Formula $\log(y)$
\end_inset

 typically yield similar results to those based on 
\begin_inset Formula $\exp(y)$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), although differences in explained variance can still affect poverty estimates.
 The number of donors (i.e.
 neighbors) is determined by the practitioner.
 While setting this number to one can result in repeated values—especially
 when model fit is weak—
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 recommends using five neighbors.
 He also emphasizes that this choice should be adaptive, depending on the
 sample size and the model’s explanatory power, as measured by its 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Assuming that equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:welfare model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is fit via OLS and ignoring sampling weights, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 will be equal to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\beta}=(X'X)^{-1}X'y\label{eq:b1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
or, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $X'\beta+e$
\end_inset

, one gets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\beta}=\beta+(X'X)^{-1}X'e\label{eq:b2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Imputing to a contemporaneous survey
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:sametime"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Imputation of poverty to a contemporaneous survey can be a useful tool.
 For example, assume a country collects a living standard survey annually
 and has also collected a Demographic and Health Survey (DHS).
 If one would like to determine how nutritional indicators among children
 vary across the welfare distribution, survey to survey imputation may be
 of use to determine this.
 Nevertheless, practitioners could also impute the indicator of interest
 to the living standards survey.
 For example, with the goal of determining energy poverty in Bulgaria, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rude2024statistical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 impute energy spending from the household budget survey (HBS) to the European
 Survey of Income and Living Conditions to determine profiles of the energy
 poor.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These applications resemble a problem considered by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rubin1986statistical"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where no single data set contains the complete set of variables for inference,
 where imputations are made both ways.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The successful application of survey-to-survey imputation depends on meeting
 several critical preconditions, first outlined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "jesko1998"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and later refined by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These preconditions ensure that the fundamental assumption – both surveys
 represent the same underlying population – holds true.
 Having 2 contemporaneous surveys which represent the same population are
 needed for the approach to work well.
 In this instance, the tendency of S2S methods to replicate the distribution
 of the source data in the target data is considered an advantage.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Covariate comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variables used to predict welfare must be present and measured consistently
 in both source and target surveys, they should be representative of the
 same population for a given period.
 This requirement extends beyond simple presence of the covariates to encompass:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Identical definitions of key variables 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Consistent measurement approaches 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar survey implementation protocols
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Distribution Alignment
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the method to work effectively, both surveys must exhibit three types
 of consistency:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Similar distributions of predictor variables.
 Each covariate should have similar summary statistics across surveys.
 This includes both averages and measures of spread/variation
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Example: The distribution of education levels should be comparable across
 surveys.
 Not just means, but other moments should be aligned.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Stable structural relationships between variables
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The correlation patterns between predictors should be preserved
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Example: If education strongly predicts formal employment in the source
 survey, this relationship should hold in the target survey.
 Changes in these relationships may indicate structural economic changes
 that could invalidate the model's predictions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For predictions in the same time period this is a desirable feature as it
 will allow for an accurate replication of the welfare distribution.
 In the case of imputing to a Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) it would
 allow for accurate estimation of stunting rates across welfare quantiles.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
A consistent definition of covariates across training and target surveys
 is also crucial.
 For instance, household size must be defined uniformly across surveys.
 If one survey counts only members sharing five or more meals per week while
 another uses a different definition, this violates not just the first requireme
nt (similar distributions) but potentially the second as well, as it affects
 both the variable's distribution and its relationships with other predictors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Model Assumptions 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reliability of welfare predictions depends critically on meeting the
 model's statistical assumptions, particularly:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Normal distribution of residuals, although this can be relaxed as noted
 in the previous section 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
When the normality assumptions are violated, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 provide evidence that appropriate transformations of the dependent variable
 may help achieve normality.
 In cases where transformations prove insufficient, practitioners may draw
 residuals from their empirical distribution, though this requires the assumptio
n of symmetric errors around zero.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Homoscedasticity of error terms, although this can be relaxed by modeling
 for heteroskedasticity
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2002micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harvey1976estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offer methods that allow for modelling heteroskedasticity
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Linear relationships between predictors and welfare, this too can be relaxed
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Using polynomials in a linear model or the use of methods like random forest
 or gradient boosting can help relax the linearity assumption
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Imputing across time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation provides a valuable tool for filling gaps
 in welfare data, but its use over time requires greater caution than for
 contemporaneous applications as discussed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Survey-to-Survey-Imputation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The core assumption—that changes in welfare reflect only shifts in observable
 characteristics, with stable relationships between covariates and welfare—becom
es increasingly fragile as the time between surveys grows.
 Structural economic change, evolving labor markets, and shifting household
 behaviors can all violate this assumption, leading to imputation errors
 that distort actual welfare dynamics.
 Moreover, S2S methods tend to reproduce the welfare distribution of the
 source survey: coefficients capture the joint distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 from the source period, and errors are drawn from that same model in the
 source data.
 As a result, households with identical characteristics in the source and
 target periods are assigned identical poverty probabilities, regardless
 of contextual changes.
 The same limitations that affect contemporaneous S2S imputation—chiefly,
 its tendency to replicate the structure of the source data—are likely to
 be amplified when imputing across time, further constraining the method’s
 ability to track true changes in poverty and inequality.
 Given the growing reliance on S2S for poverty monitoring, even subtle distortio
ns can mislead policy.
 Practitioners should therefore apply these methods with caution, rigorously
 test validity across time periods, and clearly communicate the method's
 limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
The Variance Decomposition Challenge
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The core challenge lies in the decomposition of empirical welfare variance
 into two components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The explicable empirical variance captured by the model: 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]=\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i}\left(x_{i}\hat{\beta}-\bar{x}\hat{\beta}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The unexplained random component: (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In well-specified models, the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 typically ranges from 0.40 to 0.60, meaning that a substantial portion of
 welfare variation remains unexplained.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 statistic represents the proportion of variance explained by the model:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R^{2}=\frac{\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]}{\left(\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When imputing across time, practitioners must rely on an error distribution
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

) estimated from historical data, same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 This implicitly assumes that households with the same characteristics face
 the same probability of being poor across different time periods.
 However, a critical limitation arises from the assumption of constant parameter
s over time.
 In reality, parameters often change, especially in rapidly developing countries
 or over long time horizons, as highlighted in micro decomposition techniques
 such as those of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "bourguignon2008beyond"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This implies that the estimated contributions of changes in characteristics
 may not fully reflect actual poverty or inequality levels but rather the
 role of compositional shifts in shaping welfare evolution.
 In other words, instead of measuring the true welfare distribution, the
 method may only capture the effect of compositional shifts – how the population
’s characteristics are changing over time.
 The assumption of stable parameters when characteristics change significantly
 becomes increasingly restrictive, leading to potential bias in predicted
 welfare levels.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This concern can also be seen directly from the regression equation: 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\left(X'X\right)^{-1}X'y$
\end_inset

.
 When the distribution of covariates 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 changes substantially (whether due to structural transformation, demographic
 shifts, or policy reforms) both 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X'X\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X'y$
\end_inset

 change.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A possible avenue for improvement is to explore methods that allow for parameter
 variation over time.
 This could involve explicitly modeling 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{t}$
\end_inset

 as a function of time or estimating it using repeated cross-sections or
 panel data, where available.
 Such an approach could help relax the assumption of constant coefficients
 and possibly improve the reliability of survey-to-survey imputations in
 dynamic contexts.
 However, such an approach is not readily found in the literature.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Population-Level Implications
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The predicted poverty rates for the population depend on:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The distribution of household characteristics in the target period
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The stability of relationships between these characteristics and welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The assumed consistency of unobserved factors affecting welfare
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that welfare is log-normal and independence between the mean (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\beta$
\end_inset

) and the idiosyncratic component, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

, then for the population, poverty is given by: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
FGT_{0}=Φ\,\left(\frac{\ln z-\bar{X}_{target}\hat{\beta}}{\sqrt{\mathrm{var}\left[X_{target}\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}}}\right)\label{eq:var pov}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Mathematically, this translates to predictions, for any given poverty line,
 depending on both the mean transformed welfare 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{X}_{target}\hat{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 and its variation 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathrm{var}\left[X_{target}\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sources of Temporal Instability
\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Several factors can undermine the method's reliability across time:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Structural changes in welfare determinants (e.g., educational convergence)
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sampling differences between surveys 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Policy changes (e.g., new welfare programs) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Economic shocks or systemic changes (e.g., currency reforms)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The reliability of survey design over time, including consistency in variable
 definitions, data collection methods (e.g., in-person vs.
 phone), and other methodological changes that may affect comparability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These implications extend beyond model specification.
 Many S2S applications employ stepwise regression or regularization techniques
 (like lasso or ridge regression) to optimize model fit, often measured
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 While some argue that endogeneity and omitted variable bias are less concerning
 in predictive modeling,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "dang2025poverty"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 note that endogeneity is not a concern.
 An endogenous variable is frequently defined as an explanatory variable
 that may be correlated with the error term (Wooldridge, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citebyear
key "wooldridge2009introductory"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 p88).
 Omitted variables are related as these are correlated to the error term
 and a covariate.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 these issues become particularly problematic when applying models across
 time periods.
 A model trained on data from one year may produce biased estimates when
 used to predict welfare in another year, as both omitted variables and
 endogeneity can significantly impact the model's temporal stability and
 will likely cause biased estimates limiting the usefulness of S2S to predict
 poverty in years where a welfare aggregate is unavailable (see Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Implications for Inequality Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenges noted in previous sections extend to inequality measurement.
 The reliance on error distributions obtained from a different point in
 time, particularly affects inequality measurement.
 Under the common assumption of log-normally distributed welfare, the Gini
 coefficient depends critically on the welfare distribution's standard deviation.
 Using an outdated error distribution can thus produce misleading inequality
 estimates, even when mean predictions appear reasonable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming that welfare is log-normally distributed then Gini is equal to
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "crow1987lognormal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

): 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Gini=2Φ(\frac{σ}{\sqrt{2}})-1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $σ$
\end_inset

 is the empirical standard deviation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, the imputed Gini across time is also dependent on 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{σ}{}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

, which is estimated in an older survey and the resulting empirical variance
 of the linear fit,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]$
\end_inset

, in the target survey since the empirical variance of the lognormally distribut
ed 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 could be decomposed by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
σ^{2}=\mathrm{var}\left[x_{target}\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}{}_{e}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and consequently, is also subject to changes in the sample’s distribution
 of the observed characteristics used in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method's tendency to replicate the welfare distribution of the source
 survey can make it unreliable for measuring changes in inequality and poverty.
 This suggests that survey-to-survey imputation across time periods should
 be approached with considerable caution, particularly when economic conditions
 or social structures have changed significantly between the source and
 target periods.
 Given the increasing reliance on these methods to fill data gaps in poverty
 monitoring, it is crucial to clearly communicate their limitations to avoid
 misinterpretation of trends.
 Moreover, imputed poverty estimates should be systematically validated
 against other proxies for household welfare, such as national accounts,
 labor market indicators, and administrative data, to ensure consistency
 and identify potential discrepancies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model Based Simulations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section builds on the concepts introduced in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-basics-behind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, focusing on the effects of violating the underlying assumptions of survey-to-s
urvey imputation on imputed poverty estimates.
 Using simulated data, a controlled environment is created to systematically
 examine these effects.
 Model-based simulations leverage the assumptions underlying the imputation
 models to investigate their robustness and identify potential points of
 failure.
 Unlike real-world data, model based simulations allow for precise manipulation
 of individual components, enabling a clearer understanding of how specific
 changes impact the model's estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Creating populations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Creating-populations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We create 1,000 populations of 20,000 households where the welfare of the
 population is generated with the following data generating process (DGP):
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln y_{i}=3+0.1x_{1_{i}}+0.5x_{2_{i}}-0.25x_{3_{i}}+0.2x_{4_{i}}-0.15x_{5_{i}}+e_{i}\label{eq:dgp_model}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,0.5^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a discrete variable, simulated as the rounded integer value of the maximum
 between 1 and a random Poisson variable with mean 
\begin_inset Formula $λ=4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.5 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, otherwise it is equal to 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}\sim N(2.5,2^{2})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 is a variable drawn from a Student’s t distribution with 5 degrees of freedom
 and scaled by 0.25
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gini for this distribution is ~0.38, and the covariates explain roughly
 47 percent of the variation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ln y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 For the examples presented in the following sections, source and target
 sample data will be taken from each population.
 In this experiment, we take a grid of 20 poverty thresholds, corresponding
 to every 5th percentile up to the 95th percentile of each population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:DGP_cluster"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we present a different DGP which follows an assumed double nested error
 model similar to that of small area estimation based on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ea7f7e4f-7381-39b0-abdd-8da14c150408"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 although covariate generation has been updated to follow the one presented
 here.
 This adjusted DGP is used to illustrate the limited impact on bias when
 the DGP clearly follows a clustered or nested error yet the modeling ignores
 this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How to Impute?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The typical imputation approach undertaken for S2S work done to predict
 poverty, follows the literature on multiple imputation (MI).
 A similar method was followed in the original software implementation of
 small area estimation proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, PovMap (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Under the MI approach, the parameters estimated on the training data are
 not applied directly to the target data, instead the parameters to be applied
 to the target data are drawn from their posterior distributions as illustrated
 in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-basics-behind"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For small area estimation, the imputation approach from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2003micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 has been updated to follow the approach from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See a detailed discussion in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "rodas2021pull,corral2021map"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Under the method of the latter, the parameters estimated using the training
 data are applied directly to the data and noise is estimated via a parametric
 bootstrap which is aligned to the model's assumptions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gonzalez-manteiga2008bootstrap"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To compare different imputation methods, a simple random sample (SRS) comprising
 20 percent of the data generated in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is used as both source and target data.
 In the results presented in this section, the same dataset is used for
 both model development and prediction.
 This approach eliminates potential additional noise introduced by sampling
 variability, allowing for a more controlled assessment of imputation performanc
e that is entirely driven by the model fit and its assumptions.
 The process is applied across 1,000 generated populations allowing us to
 assess the method's empirical bias.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Why simulate the errors?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation of poverty is not simply about predicting
 the dependent variable.
 Relying solely on the predicted value of welfare to derive poverty rates
 often yields poor results.
 This section uses the synthetic population introduced in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to illustrate this point.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We fit a linear model on a simple random sample (SRS) comprising 20 percent
 of the population.
 This model is then used to generate two sets of predicted values for the
 full data:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The linear prediction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y_{i}}=x_{i}\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The linear prediction plus a randomly drawn error: 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}^{*}=x_{i}\hat{\beta}+e_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}^{*}$
\end_inset

 is drawn from 
\begin_inset Formula $N(0,\hat{\sigma}^{2})$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:why_errors"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 hows that relying solely on the linear prediction, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\hat{\beta},$
\end_inset

 fails to replicate the true distribution of welfare.
 For example, if the true poverty line is 2.39—corresponding to a 20 percent
 poverty rate in the actual data—then the linear prediction alone would
 imply a poverty rate of only 10 percent.
 This gap persists despite the fact that the linear prediction has a lower
 mean squared error (MSE = 0.25) than the version with stochastic error (MSE
 = 0.5).
 This demonstrates that minimizing MSE is not sufficient for reproducing
 the distributional properties needed to estimate poverty accurately.
 Moreover, the Spearman rank correlation is higher for the linear prediction
 than for the version with added error.
 In other words, correctly ranking households is also not enough to replicate
 the full welfare distribution or derive accurate poverty statistics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Replicating the actual distribution, with and without simulated errors 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:why_errors"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/why_errors.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 True values correspond to those generated following Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dgp_model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, XB are the predicted linear fit on to the full data, and XB+e is the predicted
 linear fit plus a random error following the estimated distribution from
 the model.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This underscores a central point: accurate estimation of poverty through
 S2S imputation requires more than good point predictions or rankings.
 It requires replicating the underlying distribution of welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Under a normal error DGP
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The baseline imputation methods assume that welfare is linearly related
 to a set of characteristics and that errors follow a normal distribution
 with same variance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The data generation process (DGP) used to simulate the dataset adheres
 to these assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under this simulation setup, the prediction bias across different approaches
 remains minimal across various poverty lines, indicating that all methods
 effectively replicate the underlying welfare distribution (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_eb_mi"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Although the "Fixed B" method – where parameters are directly applied (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fixed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) – produces the lowest bias, the differences between methods are negligible.
 Even in the most biased case observed in this simulation, the discrepancy
 is less than 0.025 percentage points.
 Additionally, the number of imputations performed under multiple imputation
 (MI) appears to have minimal impact on bias (Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 under MI and direct application of parameters 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_eb_mi"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/mi_ebp_fgt0.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
 
\series bold
Fixed B
\series default
: uses the method described in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fixed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to generate predictions.
 For each of 100 Monte Carlo (MC) simulations, poverty is estimated at each
 threshold and then averaged across simulations to produce the final estimate.
 
\series bold
MI X
\series default
: implements X imputations following Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, poverty is estimated for each threshold under each imputed vector, and
 the results are averaged across simulations to obtain the final estimate.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Under non-normally distributed errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is essential to ensure the imputation method chosen is the one best aligned
 to the data at hand.
 Data transformations, to ensure the model assumptions are met can help
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "rojas2020data,corral2021map"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), but there are instances where transformations are of little use.
 If the residuals do not follow a normal distribution, an alternative is
 to draw from the empirical residuals.
 Stata's 
\family typewriter
mi regress
\family default
 includes a bootstrap option that estimates posterior parameters from bootstrap
 samples, addressing concerns about asymptotic normality when parameter
 assumptions are questionable (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealp
key "StataCorp2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
mi impute regress
\family default
 p2.).
 Similarly, the 
\family typewriter
hetmireg
\family default
 command,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
hetmireg
\family default
 (Corral - mimeo) command supports heteroskedasticity following the alpha
 model described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2002micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Corral (mimeo) - https://github.com/pcorralrodas/hetmireg
\end_layout

\end_inset

 inspired from PovMap methods (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), generates bootstrap samples with errors drawn from the empirical distribution
, though it omits the area random effect required for area-level estimates
 necessary for small area estimation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent advancements have introduced machine learning (ML) techniques for
 estimation, but since most ML methods lack explicit assumptions about error
 term distributions, they cannot be directly applied.
 Instead, bootstrap-based alternatives, implemented in PovMap (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citealt
key "zhao2006user"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) and Stata’s 
\family typewriter
sae
\family default
 command 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "nguyen2018sae"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, have proven effective, particularly for regularized regression techniques
 like lasso regression as shown by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "lucchetti2024application"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 These methods could be extended to other ML approaches, including gradient
 boosting, random forests, and Bayesian additive regression trees.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "verme2024predicting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 offers a useful primer on the performance of random forests and other ML
 approaches in poverty prediction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 of different methods under non-normal errors 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_eb_mi-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/method_comp_fgt0_rf_t.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/method_comp_fgt0_t.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but errors are simulated from a Student's t-distribution with 10 degrees
 of freedom and scaled for a SD of 0.5.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
 
\series bold
Fixed B
\series default
: uses the method described in Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Fixed"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to generate predictions.
 For each of 100 Monte Carlo (MC) simulations, poverty is estimated at each
 threshold and then averaged across simulations to produce the final estimate.
 
\series bold
Fixed B lnskew
\series default
: follows the same approach as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fixed B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but the dependent variable is transformed using a zero-skewness log transformat
ion.
 
\series bold
Fixed B bcskew
\series default
: follows the same approach as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fixed B
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but the dependent variable is transformed using a Box-Cox transformation.
 
\series bold
MI X
\series default
: implements X imputations following Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:MI"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, poverty is estimated for each threshold under each imputed vector, and
 the results are averaged across simulations to obtain the final estimate.
 
\series bold
MI X BS
\series default
: same as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

MI X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but uses Stata's bootstrap option.
 
\series bold
OLS BS
\series default
: Fits the model on bootstrap samples drawn using simple random sampling
 (SRS), applies the estimated parameters to the target data, and draws residuals
 from their empirical distribution.
 
\series bold
lasso BIC
\series default
: applies parameters from lasso model where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is selected using the Bayesian information criterion (BIC) function and
 residuals for each imputation are randomly drawn from the predicted residuals.
 
\series bold
Random Forest:
\series default
 applies parameter estimates from a random forest model to the target data,
 with residuals for each imputation randomly drawn from the distribution
 of predicted residuals.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Results from a simulation where the DGP is adjusted and errors are simulated
 from a Student's t-distribution with 10 degrees of freedom and scaled for
 a SD of 0.5 are presented in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_eb_mi-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Results from this simulation seem to suggest that random forest prediction
 coupled with residuals drawn from their empirical distribution yield the
 most biased estimates, although if the poverty line were at the 50th percentile
 it would be deemed unbiased if other percentiles are ignored (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_eb_mi-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, left).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Perhaps under better tuning of the random forest model the bias can be reduced,
 although for simplicity the basic options of the command are used here.
 Nevertheless, if classification were the objective, random forest appears
 to do a much better job than OLS (Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:rforest_matrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ols_matrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Under this type of errors, the applied data transformations are of limited
 use (Fig.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_eb_mi-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, right - 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fixed B, lnskew
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Fixed B, bcskew
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Zero-skewness log (lnskew) or Box-Cox transformation (bcskew).
 Both can be easily implemented in Stata by using the commands: lnskew0
 and bcskew0.
 If weights are needed, users can use lnskew0w, a modified version of lnskew0
 within Stata's SAE package.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Additionally, Stata's 
\family typewriter
mi regress 
\family default
with the bootstrap option does not yield considerable improvement under
 this simulation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Stata's documentation for the option is unexpectedly short and provides
 few details on the method's implementation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Drawing residuals from their empirical distribution seems to yield the
 best results under this simulation where errors follow a Student's t-distributi
on with 10 degrees of freedom and scaled for a SD of 0.5.
 Both the lasso model fitting, paired with residuals drawn from the empirical
 distribution and an OLS with residuals drawn in the same way yield the
 least biased estimates.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The OLS implementation relies on the 
\family typewriter
hetmireg
\family default
 command by Corral (mimeo) - https://github.com/pcorralrodas/hetmireg.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Motivated by the unexpectedly poor performance of random forests in predicting
 poverty levels, particularly given the results presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "verme2024predicting"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we also examined their classification ability in a separate simulation
 using normally distributed errors.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The data used follows those presented in Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:DGP_cluster"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 This distinction is relevant for Proxy Means Testing (PMT), where the goal
 is not to predict continuous consumption or income, but rather to assign
 households to eligibility categories.
 As 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "grosh1995proxy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 emphasize, PMT prioritizes classification accuracy over predictive precision.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this context, when evaluated in-sample, random forests outperform OLS
 in classification tasks—even though OLS is more closely aligned with the
 true data-generating process (Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:rforest_matrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ols_matrix"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 When applied to the same data used for modeling, random forest classifies
 households with notably higher accuracy.
 However, this advantage disappears when applied to the entire population
 (i.e., from where the SRS sample was taken from) where the classification
 performance of random forests closely matches that of OLS (Tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:rforest_matrix-oos"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:ols_matrix-oos"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This suggests that random forests in this example is overfitting in the
 training sample, underscoring the importance of cross-validation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In the simulations conducted here, given that the true DGP is known, model
 selection and tuning is not undertaken.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pattern is also evident in the mean squared residuals: in-sample, random
 forests achieve a low mean squared residual of 0.075, compared to 0.20 for
 OLS.
 When looking at out-of-sample results, however, the random forest residuals
 increase to 0.19, converging toward the OLS out-of-sample value of 0.20.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Under heteroskedastic errors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An additional simulation is conducted where the error distribution of the
 DGP is modified to follow heteroskedastic errors.
 The errors are designed to mimic a situation where the uncertainty or variabili
ty in the dependent variable grows as an independent variable increases.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The variance of the error term is: 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=\frac{\exp\left((1/6)x\right)}{2}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x\sim N(0.5,0.5)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 Under this simulation, data transformations are also of little help (Fig.
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_het"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

), and are aligned to the statement made by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "betti2024attempt"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 who point out that ignoring heteroskedasticity can lead to biased estimates.
 It seems like the best answer for heteroskedasticity is to address it directly
 via the model.
 However, the alpha model from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2002micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 does not seem to align as well to the DGP implemented here as the method
 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harvey1976estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 but fit with MLE (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Alpha model
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 vs.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Het.
 MLE
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The method from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "harvey1976estimating"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is applied via Stata's 
\family typewriter
hetregress
\family default
 command.
 While the alpha model from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "elbers2002micro"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is applied using 
\family typewriter
hetmireg.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Finally, a lasso model coupled with residuals drawn from their empirical
 distribution also yields solid results.
 This last result suggests that drawing from the empirical distribution
 may be a robust option when one is uncertain about the distribution.
\end_layout

