\begin_layout Subsubsection
PMM - A flexible imputation approach 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A common alternative imputation approach, predictive mean matching (PMM),
 differs in its simulation strategy.
 Rather than drawing residuals or estimating parameters from a posterior
 distribution, PMM matches observations from the source dataset to those
 in the target dataset based on predicted values, ensuring that imputed
 values remain within the observed range of the source data.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Predictions typically rely on OLS, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "lucchetti2024application"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for an application to lasso model fitting.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 This method is particularly useful when handling non-normal or discontinuous
 distributions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "SwiftMethod"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, its reliance on observed values limits its ability to capture
 shifts in economic conditions between periods, similar to other approaches
 presented in the section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate PMM’s limitations, a simulation is conducted where a covariate
 distribution in the target dataset is altered, creating a mismatch with
 the source data.
 Under the simulation, the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 variable is adjusted to take a value of 1 when a random uniform number
 between 0 and 1 is less than 0.8 instead of the original 0.2.
 This is only done for the target data.
 The model is fit on the original data, but the imputations are made on
 the adjusted data.
 Despite this shift, PMM follows OLS-based predictions closely (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_pmm"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, in a second simulation where economic growth of 20 percent is
 introduced between the source and target periods,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The only change introduced is a change in the constant term, everything
 else remains equal between source and target data.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 PMM fails to capture the distributional shift (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_pmm-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This highlights a critical limitation of PMM as well as other methods illustrat
ed: when substantial economic or structural changes occur between data collectio
n periods, the methods may not be appropriate for imputing poverty estimates.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Difference in FGT0 under PMM imputations 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_pmm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/method_comp_PMMpp1.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
