\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/method_comp_PMMpp.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Difference is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution
 of the source data.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
 
\series bold
Predicted change: 
\series default
applies PMM imputation using Stata's 
\family typewriter
impute pmm
\family default
 command.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These findings underscore that no single imputation method is universally
 optimal.
 The choice of approach should be guided by the data’s properties, the error
 distribution, and the degree of economic and social change between surveys.
 Parametric methods can introduce bias when their assumptions are violated,
 while empirical residual drawing and heteroskedasticity-aware models tend
 to offer more robust alternatives.
 Machine learning techniques, particularly when combined with bootstrapping,
 also show promise for future applications.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simulation results demonstrate that while many imputation methods perform
 well under ideal conditions, their effectiveness varies considerably when
 faced with different error structures and data characteristics.
 Direct application of parameters ("Fixed B") yields low bias under normal
 error distributions, but when assumptions are violated—as with Student’s
 t-distributed or heteroskedastic errors—methods using empirical residual
 drawing perform better.
 Machine learning approaches, such as lasso regression combined with empirical
 residuals, show potential but require careful implementation.
 Conversely, the limitations of Predictive Mean Matching (PMM) become more
 pronounced when economic conditions change between the training and target
 periods—though, such instability can affect all models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall, these results highlight the importance of selecting imputation
 methods that are well-suited to the specific data context, error distribution,
 and stability of conditions across surveys.
 Future work could usefully extend bootstrap-based techniques to a wider
 range of machine learning methods, while ensuring robust error estimation
 remains central.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Noise estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A word of caution is warranted here and it is related to how noise is estimated.
 When applying MI methods the noise is typically estimated using Rubin's
 rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rubin1987multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Under Rubin's rules the estimated variance is equal to the sum of within-imputa
tion variance, the between imputation variance, and the between imputation
 variance divided by the number of imputations.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Under Rubin's rules: 
\begin_inset Formula $T=W+(1+\frac{1}{M})B$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the total variance, 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is the number of imputations, 
\begin_inset Formula $W$
\end_inset

 is the within survey variance, and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the between imputation variance.
 Based on Rubin's rules, the imputed indicator cannot have a variance that
 is smaller than it would have if it were collected directly in the target
 survey.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 It is important to remember that these methods were developed for regression
 analysis, where a variable with missing observations is imputed and then
 used in a model.
 Rubin's rules are applied in those instances to obtain a valid standard
 error of the regression parameters.
 Estimating the prediction's noise in a similar manner when parameters are
 applied directly risks producing improper imputations.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "van2018flexible"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 notes how keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta s$
\end_inset

 fixed across imputations can lead to improper imputations since the goal
 of MI is not to minimize the MSE.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When keeping 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 fixed, as is done by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "molina2010small"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, MSEs are estimated following a parametric bootstrap presented by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "gonzalez-manteiga2008bootstrap"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 This bootstrap procedure is aligned to the model's assumptions under small
 area estimation, but the approach may not necessarily align with multiple
 imputation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Difference in noise estimation under MI and parametric bootstrap 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:MSE_comp"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/method_comp_MSE.eps
	lyxscale 80
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Data are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 MSE is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simulation is run to test how aligned to the truth are the two methods
 – 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "rubin1987multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

's rules and parametric bootstrap – for noise estimation.
 Populations of 20,000 observations are generated following the model's
 assumptions as illustrated in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 A random sample of 30 percent is marked as the target survey, and a random
 sample of 20 percent is marked as the source data for training the model.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The samples are selected separately and may have an overlap in observations.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 To compare the noise estimates of each method, 10,000 populations are created.
 Under each population a new error is drawn from its assumed distribution
 and predictions are made, as well as noise is estimated – following a parametri
c bootstrap 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "gonzalez-manteiga2008bootstrap"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or following Rubin's rules 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "rubin1987multiple"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Both methods here appear to overestimate the true MSE.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The method's MSE/variance is the average from the 10,000 imputations.
 The empirical MSE is: 
\begin_inset Formula $MSE=\sum_{b=1}\frac{\left(\hat{\tau}_{b}-\tau_{b}\right)^{2}}{B}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 is the indicator of interest and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the total number of bootstrap populations.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The reason for the overestimation is that both methods measure the noise
 based on the target survey which is smaller than the population.
 The MSE is equal to the sum of the squared bias and the variance of the
 indicator of interest.
 Since both methods are nearly unbiased, it mostly boils down to the variance
 and given that the target survey is much smaller than the population the
 variance parameter of the MSE is larger (see Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:sample_size_mse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 However, further caution is warranted in instances where the estimates
 are likely biased since the variance estimated following Rubin's rules
 will yield a downward biased estimate of the true noise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Imputations under biased samples
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation methods are often applied to biased samples,
 such as when specific population segments are systematically underrepresented.
 To address this issue, practitioners commonly attempt two corrective strategies
: re-weighting the sample or standardizing covariates.
 This section examines these methods and evaluates their effectiveness using
 simulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Extracting samples 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Extracting-samples"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Under each of the 1,000 populations created in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the following samples are taken: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Random sample: a 20 percent simple random sample (SRS) of the population.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Bottom biased sample: here, the poorest quintile is purposely undersampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For the top 80, take a SRS for each centile, 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the bottom 20, take a 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 percent as a sample.
 This means that for the 20th centile an SRS sample of 20% is taken, for
 the 19th centile, 19 percent is sampled, for the 18th centile, 18 percent
 is sampled, and so forth.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Biased sample top and bottom: Create a biased sample, where the poorest
 quintile and the richest quintile are purposely under sampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For the top 20, sample 
\begin_inset Formula $100-c$
\end_inset

 percent.
 This means that for the 80th centile, an SRS sample of 20 percent is taken,
 for the 81st centile a sample of 19 percent is taken, for the 82nd centile,
 18 percent is sampled, and so forth.
 Note that we do not sample the top 1 percent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For the bottom 20, we sample 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 percent.
 This means that for the 20th centile an SRS sample of 20 percent is taken,
 for the 19th centile, 19 percent is sampled, for the 18th centile, 18 percent
 is sampled, and so forth.
 Note that the bottom 1 percent is not sampled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For all other centiles (21-79), an SRS sample by centile is taken.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Re-weighting the target sample
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Re-weighting involves adjusting the sampling weights in the target survey
 to align its characteristics with those of the overall population.
 One common approach, minimum cross-entropy,
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When the original sampling weights of the target survey are ignored, it
 is assumed that every observation had a similar probability of being selected,
 then the re-weighting method is max-entropy (see Golan, Judge and Miller
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeyearpar
key "GolanBook"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a more thorough exposition of maximum entropy).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 modifies the weights to match constraints like the mean or variance of
 key covariates.
 While theoretically sound, re-weighting assumes that adjusted weights can
 restore the representativeness of a biased sample.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To test the problems with biased samples and re-weighting, two sampling
 scenarios are used as an illustrative example.
 The samples are taken from a population created as described in section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For the biased sample exercise, three possible re-weighting scenarios are
 considered:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Re-weighting is done using Stata's user created command 
\family typewriter
wentropy
\family default
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Corral_Rodas_wentropy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The command is used instead of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "wittenberg2010introduction"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
maxentropy
\family default
 command due to 
\family typewriter
wentropy
\family default
 adding more flexibility and because it provides solutions to instances
 where 
\family typewriter
maxentropy
\family default
 fails.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Covariate match:
\series default
 The mean of each covariate from the simple random sample is used as a benchmark
 to adjust the weights of the biased samples.
 Re-weighting is performed using minimum cross-entropy, which modifies the
 prior weights as minimally as possible to ensure that the adjusted sample
 meets the specified constraints, namely the covariate means.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Linear fit match:
\series default
 The mean of the model's linear fit from the simple random sample is used
 to adjust the weights of the biased samples.
 This calibration is performed using minimum cross-entropy, ensuring that
 the prior weights are modified as minimally as necessary to satisfy the
 constraint of matching the linear fit's mean.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Linear fit & variance match:
\series default
 The linear fit’s 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 and 
\series bold
variance
\series default
 of the simple random sample are used to calibrate the weights of the biased
 samples.
 Weights are calibrated using minimum cross-entropy to adjust prior weights
 by the smallest amount possible so that the constraints (i.e., the mean and
 the variance of the linear fit) are satisfied.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the simulated data does not have sampling weights, the priors are
 equal to 1 and thus minimum cross-entropy is in reality max-entropy in
 this instance.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Standardizing covariates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standardizing covariates offers a straightforward approach to addressing
 disparities between survey samples.
 Using data from the source survey (or training data), where the model is
 initially estimated, practitioners can leverage the known means and variances
 of each covariate to adjust the corresponding variables in the target survey.
 This alignment ensures that the mean and variance of covariates in the
 imputed data match those of the source data, enhancing comparability.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "dang2017"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 advocate this approach as a practical solution for reconciling differences
 between survey samples.
 Their application of the method to Jordanian data suggests that it can
 yield valid results under certain conditions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The method's efficacy depends on the assumption that covariates follow a
 normal distribution – an assumption that may not hold universally.
 To assess the robustness of this approach, the samples described in Section
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 were used, despite the fact that the covariates in this case deviate from
 normality.
 The adjustment process involves scaling and centering the covariates from
 the target survey so that their means and variances align with those of
 the source survey, as shown in the following formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x_{target}^{'}=(x_{target}-\hat{\mu}_{x_{target}})\frac{\hat{\sigma}_{x}}{\hat{\sigma}_{x_{target}}}+\hat{\mu}_{x}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two standardization scenarios are implemented:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Standardize each X
\series default
: The 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 of each covariate from the simple random sample is used as a benchmark
 to adjust the 
\series bold
mean 
\series default
and
\series bold
 standard deviation
\series default
 of the biased samples.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Standardize XB
\series default
: The linear fit’s (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}=x\hat{\beta}$
\end_inset

) 
\series bold
mean
\series default
 and 
\series bold
standard deviation
\series default
 of the simple random sample are used to standardize the linear fit of the
 biased target samples.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Results
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Results_simdata"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To isolate the impact of biased sampling in the target data and assess the
 effectiveness of correction methods, the analysis avoids introducing additional
 sources of error by using the true values for the coefficients (
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

) and error distribution (
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

) applied in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Hence, instead of fitting a model, the actual values of the linear fit
 from Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dgp_model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are used.
 For each sample created in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 100 vectors were generated by combining the true 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 with a randomly drawn error term 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}\sim N(0,0.5^{2})$
\end_inset

 for every observation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that the true value is used and not its estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Poverty and Gini coefficients were then calculated for each of these 100
 vectors using either re-weighted survey weights or standardized covariates.
 The final estimates were obtained by averaging across the 100 simulations,
 and bias was determined by comparing these estimates to the true population
 values across the 1,000 populations, resulting in a robust evaluation of
 the methods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Standard sampling bias-correction techniques, such as re-weighting to match
 population means, may be insufficient when source and target surveys differ
 fundamentally—i.e., when they do not appear to capture the same underlying
 population, with differing moments of the covariate distributions and altered
 relationships (covariances) between covariates and outcomes.
 In such cases, large differences in the covariate distributions suggest
 that the two surveys do not represent the same underlying population.
 This limitation becomes evident in bottom-biased samples, where the poorest
 segments of the population were underrepresented, leading to systematic
 underestimation of poverty levels across the welfare distribution (Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Unadjusted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 Efforts to address this bias by adjusting survey weights to match covariate
 means had no noticeable effect (“Match X”).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since the weights assume no priors, these are in fact calculated using maximum
 entropy.
 When prior weights are considered the method adjusts the existing weights
 by the smallest possible amount to ensure the constraints match, this is
 known as cross-entropy.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Incorporating additional constraints to the maximum entropy algorithm,
 such as aligning both means and variances of covariates, provided marginal
 improvements but failed to address the core issue of sampling distortion
 (“Match X and var[X]”).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 under bottom biased samples (Sec 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and different correction measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_reweight"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/weights_std_bb_fgt0.eps
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Target samples are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in FGT0 under top and bottom biased samples (Sec 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and different correction measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_reweight-1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/weights_std_tbb_fgt0.eps
	lyxscale 25
	scale 80

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: Target samples are generated as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Bias is assessed at various poverty lines across the welfare distribution.
 Specifically, these lines correspond to percentiles that are multiples
 of 5.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A more effective approach involved aligning the mean of the linear fit of
 the model (
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

) in the target data with the average linear fit of the source data (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Match XB
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 This adjustment yielded significantly improved estimates, as did standardizing
 individual covariates (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Standardize each X
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 However, the best performing estimates incorporate the mean of the linear
 fit and the variance of the linear fit (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Match XB and var[XB]
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Standardize XB
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 These methods effectively address the interaction between mean and variance
 in determining poverty estimates, as outlined in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:var pov"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 However, it is important to note that the adjustments made here mimic the
 moments of the source data, thus when applied to other data would just
 replicate the source data's welfare distribution.
 Consequently the approaches would be of use for contemporaneous S2S, but
 not for S2S over time.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For top-and-bottom-biased samples, where both the poorest and wealthiest
 households were under-sampled, the performance of the correction methods
 mirrored the earlier findings (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Unadjusted estimates again misrepresented poverty and inequality, while
 methods that accounted for the mean and variance of the linear fit provided
 more accurate results.
 Importantly, results varied significantly across the welfare distribution.
 Biases that appeared negligible at certain thresholds, such as the 40th
 percentile, became pronounced elsewhere, highlighting the importance of
 evaluating imputations across the full distribution.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Implications for Gini Estimation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The challenges extend to inequality measurement.
 Biasing a sample by excluding low-income households reduces 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\beta\right]$
\end_inset

, which standard re-weighting methods fail to address (i.e.
 only addressing differences in the mean).
 This limitation results in downward-biased Gini estimates (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-gini"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The issue is even more pronounced for top-and-bottom-biased samples, where
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\beta\right]$
\end_inset

 is further diminished (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:bias_reweight-gini-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Adjusting weights to align both the mean and variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $x\beta$
\end_inset

 with those of the source data significantly improved the accuracy of Gini
 estimates.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Bias in Gini under bottom biased samples (Sec 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Extracting-samples"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and different correction measures 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:bias_reweight-gini"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename C:/Users/WB378870/GitHub/S2S_RTM/5.figures/weights_std_bb_gini.eps
