\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Omitted Variables 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Omitted-Variables"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Omitted variables and endogeneity have traditionally not been major concerns
 in predictions such as S2S or small area estimation.
 This is because, in the current period, any omitted variables are accounted
 for by the constant term and coefficients of covariates correlated to the
 omitted variable, which are adjusted to ensure that OLS predictions of
 the dependent variable remain unbiased.
 However, over time, the effects of omitted variables can influence predictions
 considerably.
 For a more detailed discussion, see the annex (Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a plausible application of survey-to-survey (S2S) imputation in
 a conflict-affected rural setting.
 Suppose the model predicts a decline in poverty between two survey years.
 One potential interpretation might be that poverty fell as a result of
 reduced conflict.
 However, if the model does not explicitly control for conflict, this interpreta
tion may be misleading.
 In line with guidance from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "yoshida2022concept"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the model might include fast-changing consumption indicators—such as whether
 households consumed meat, eggs, or chocolate—as proxies for welfare changes.
 Yet, if conflict both reduces consumption of these goods and suppresses
 household expenditure, then omitting conflict from the model could introduce
 omitted variable bias (OVB).
 This kind of misspecification can distort poverty estimates, particularly
 when key explanatory variables are correlated with both the outcome and
 unobserved shocks like insecurity (refer to Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To simulate the potential impact of omitted variable bias on poverty predictions
 over time the data simulated in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Creating-populations"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is expanded to include 2 new covariates: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Conflict.
 Conflict is assumed to be negatively correlated with welfare with a coefficient
 equal to -0.3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
It is simulated as a binary variable taking value 1 when a random uniform
 number between 0 and 1 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0.4$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Eggs purchased.
 The variable is assumed to be positively correlated to welfare with a coefficie
nt equal to 0.4.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
The variable is simulated as binary, taking the value 1 if a randomly drawn
 uniform number between 0 and 1 is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5x-0.5\times Conflict$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 in the baseline.
 This data generation process (DGP) reflects the negative correlation between
 conflict and the likelihood of purchasing eggs but also that it is not
 just a function of conflict but of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 as well.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Under the baseline simulation, the value for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c=0.4$
\end_inset

.
 Welfare is simulated assuming the true DGP, and thus includes conflict
 and eggs with their true coefficients.
 The prediction model is produced omitting conflict and is executed using
 the complete data to avoid other potential sources of bias (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Omitted-variable-model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 As presented in Annex 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:ann_ovb"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the coefficient on eggs is upward biased.
 Due to the omission of conflict, the constant term of the regression is
 downward biased.
 The adjustment in the constant term ensures that the model's prediction
 of the dependent variable is unbiased.
 As can be seen, omitting conflict from the model also leads to a larger
 RMSE than the truth, which will likely affect poverty predictions over
 time.
 Nevertheless, for predictions to the same period OVB has little if any
 impact (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ovb same period"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The reason for this is that even in the presence of OVB 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{var}\left[x\hat{\beta}\right]+\hat{\sigma}_{e}^{2}$
\end_inset

 will be the same to the one where conflict is present and since 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 is also equal poverty predictions in the same period are unaffected.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

