\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\size footnotesize
Note: The table reports a transition matrix estimated from simulated data.
 Each row sums to 100 and indicates the percentage of individuals originally
 in the given quintile who were classified into each predicted quintile
 based on the model’s linear fit.
 The values represent averages across 1,000 simulated populations; for each,
 a sample was drawn, the model was estimated on the sample, and subsequently
 used to classify households in a separate sample.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data generation under a two-fold nested error model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:DGP_cluster"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Data is generated for the simulations following the assumed double nested
 error model.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Data is simulated following the same approach as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which adapts the DGP from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ea7f7e4f-7381-39b0-abdd-8da14c150408"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The write-up here is also borrowed from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "corral2022guidelines"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The simulated population consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $N=20,000$
\end_inset

, distributed across 
\begin_inset Formula $A=40$
\end_inset

 areas 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a=1,\ldots,A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Within each area 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, observations are uniformly allocated over 
\begin_inset Formula $c=10$
\end_inset

 clusters 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(c_{a}=1,\ldots,C_{a}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Each cluster 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{ac}=50$
\end_inset

 observations and each area consists of 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{a}=500$
\end_inset

 observations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The outcome variable 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 is generated is generated from a linear model with additive random effects
 at the area and PSU level, and household-specific error:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ln y_{aci}=3+0.1x_{1_{i}}+0.5x_{2_{i}}-0.25x_{3_{i}}+0.2x_{4_{i}}-0.15x_{5_{i}}++\eta_{a}+\eta_{ac}+\varepsilon_{aci}\label{eq:dgp_model-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.3+0.5\frac{a}{40}+0.2\frac{c}{10}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.2.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1 is less than 0.5 as long as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=1$
\end_inset

, otherwise it is equal to 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{4}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable, taking value 1 when a random uniform number between
 0 and 1, at the household-level, is less than or equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $0.5+0.3\frac{a}{40}+0.1\frac{c}{10}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $x_{5}$
\end_inset

 is a variable drawn from a Student’s t distribution with 5 degrees of freedom
 and scaled by 0.25.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Random effects are generated as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cluster effects are simulated as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{ac}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,0.1\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Area effects as 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}\stackrel{iid}{\sim}N\left(0,0.15^{2}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Household specific residuals as 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{aci}\overset{iid}{{\sim}}N\left(0,0.5^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $c=1,\ldots,C_{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1,\ldots,A$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each of the 1,000 simulated populations, a two-stage sampling process
 is used to draw the source sample (used to train the model):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the first stage, 4 clusters are selected at random (without replacement)
 within each area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
In the second stage, 10 observations are randomly selected from each selected
 cluster.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This results in a sample of 1,600 observations per population.
 The target data is drawn using the same sampling procedure, so the target
 sample may include entirely different clusters and observations than the
 source sample.
\end_layout

\end_body
\end_document
